@article{Grundlingh1991,
abstract = {It appears that the circulation of False Bay is driven by local wind and tide. While tides may set up a simple oscillatory inflow and outflow, the wind forcing appears to be much more complex. In addition to the spatially heterogeneous wind field, data collected by Wainman et al. (1987) have shown the importance of stratification in late summer. The bay cannot be considered as a single mixed layer. Surface slicks, presumably caused by internal waves, have been observed to propagate far into the bay (e.g. into Simon's Bay). A further aspect of this stratification is the upwelling which has been observed off Cape Hangklip and Gordon's Bay. The apparent action of shelf waves in False Bay is possibly a dominant process in sub-tidal circulation. It is suggested that significant non-linear interaction between these shelf waves, wind-driven flow and tides may account for the intriguing complexity of flow in the bay. On the high-frequency side, wave-driven currents in the shallow northern reaches of the bay cannot be ignored (Shannon et al. 1983, Botes 1988). From the perspective of the water quality of the bay, the most important physical oceanographic processes are the dilution of polluted water and the subsequent exchange of this water with the adjacent open ocean. It is this exchange which ultimately will control the accumulation of pollution in False Bay.},
