@article{Crisp1964,
abstract = {The exceptionally cold period lasting from late December 1962 till early March 1963 affected to varying degrees the whole of the British Isles and much of Europe. Table 1 gives the mean minimum temperatures for a series of representative weather stations (Weather 1963a, b) at or near the west and east coasts of Britain with two more inland stations for comparison. Corrections for altitude have been applied where necessary using the average lapse rate. The mean minimum temperatures followed approximately the normal pattern of winter temperature, values declining from west to east with coastal stations slightly less cold than inland ones. However, the temperature anomalies show that the south, south- west and west coasts experienced minimum temperatures, persisting for 2 months, between 5 and 6 degrees C below the long-term average and so were relatively more severely affected than the east and north-east coasts where the anomaly was only 3-4 degrees C. The extreme north-west was, both absolutely and relatively, the least seriously influenced by the arctic spell. The temperature anomaly, rather than the temperature itself, is likely to be the critical factor determining the impact of the weather, since the balance and constitution of the fauna and flora is likely to be related to the normal temperature pattern for the locality. We should expect to look, therefore, to the south and west coasts for the most obvious consequences of frost damage and particularly to enclosed waters where the temperature is likely to drop most sharply. Fuller details of two such areas are therefore included: the Bristol Channel and the Menai Straits.},
